						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Jarhmander wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">CPUs that abandons the current multi-cycle instruction to service interrupts are not common.</div><br />I thought most major CPUs since the 68000 and 65816 could do it. They have something called a &quot;bus error&quot;, which lets a memory controller tell the processor to raise an exception because either nothing is mapped to a particular address or something is mapped that the current process should not be able to see. On the 68000 it's called /BERR; on the 65816 it's called /ABORT.</div>

